result.execSummary:
The defendant Traquil K Williams was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Reckless Driving-Cause Great Bodily Harm, a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 346.62(4).
  • Reckless Driving-Cause Great Bodily Harm, a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 346.62(4).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Attorney Jeffry R Schwartz in court.  Francesco Mineo appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Deputy court clerk:  vk  Court takes no action.

Sentencing proceeded.  Statements by the State, defense and defendant.

As to Count 1 amended:
The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of  3 YEARS CONCURRENT to any other sentence; the INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 1 YEAR; the MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 2 YEARS.

The Court stayed the sentence and placed the defendant on 3 YEARS probation. Court will allow for probation to be transfered to Indiana.

As to Count 2 amended:
The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of  3 YEARS CONCURRENT to any other sentence; the INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 1 YEAR; the MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 2 YEARS.

The Court stayed the sentence and placed the defendant on 3 YEARS probation. Court will allow for probation to be transfered to Indiana.

Court finds defendant IS eligible for the Challenge Incarceration program but IS NOT eligible the WI Substance Abuse program.  



Conditions of Probation/ Extended Supervision if revoked:
- 2 days condition time. Straight time.
- AODA assessment and cooperate with any programs deemed necessary by the probation department.
- Absolute/maintain sobriety, no alcohol, no drugs.
- Random urine screens as deemed appropriate.
- Provide a DNA sample.
- Obtain/maintain fulltime employment/education/vocation.
- Follow all rules of supervision and follow through with any other treatment deemed necessary by the department.
- No driving without a valid license.


Court ordered the defendant pay all of the following by the end of supervision.  Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment:
Restitution in the amount of $345.00 payable to Deonte S.; 
All court costs, fees, and surcharges (including DNA and any victim surcharges); 
All applicable fees of supervision, this can be based on a budget plan.
-  If revoked, the Court ordered that all court costs, fines, surcharges and/or restitution be paid through collection by the Department of Corrections from 25% of funds under Sec. 973.05(4)(b) and as a condition of extended supervision. DOC shall collect those sums.  Any amount remaining due and owing is subject to civil judgment.

Court will not allow for expungement.

Court advised defendant of his right to seek postconviction relief.

Filed:  
Written Explanation of Determinate Sentence 
Victim Impact Statement    
Notice of Right to Seek Postconviction Relief

Court stayed commencement until 08/09/2015 by 5:00pm.  If there is a stipulation, the defendant does not need to be present at the next court date.

As to Counts 1 and 2 as amended:  Defendant was advised of constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, plead NO CONTEST and was examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights and Addendum received and filed.  Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis for the plea.  Defendant further advised that if he is not a US citizen deportation is possible.  Court found defendant guilty as charged in the Information and ordered entry of Judgment of Conviction. Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon he may never possess a firearm.  Court advised defendant that his voting rights are suspended, and may not vote in any election until his civil rights are restored.
Pursuant to plea negotiations and on motion of the State, Court ordered Counts 3 and 4 dismissed and read-in to case for the purposes of sentencing.

Defendant Traquil K Williams in court with attorney Jeffry R Schwartz.  Francesco Mineo appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Filed, original amended information; copy served on defendant.  Defendant acknowledges receipt of information, waives formal reading, pleads not guilty.  
Court ordered Count 1 amended to Reckless Driving (causing great bodily harm), contrary to Wisconsin Statutes section(s) 346.62(4) and 939.50(3)(i), a Class I Felony.
Court ordered Count 2 amended to Reckless Driving (causing great bodily harm), contrary to Wisconsin Statutes section(s) 346.62(4) and 939.50(3)(i), a Class I Felony.
